<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Two</xex> is often joined with other words, forming
compounds signifying <xex>divided into</xex>, <xex>consisting of</xex>,
or <xex>having</xex>, <xex>two parts</xex>, <xex>divisions</xex>,
<xex>organs</xex>, or the like; as <xex>two</xex>-bladed,
<xex>two</xex>-celled, <xex>two</xex>-eared, <xex>two</xex>-flowered,
<xex>two</xex>hand, <xex>two</xex>-headed, <xex>two</xex>-horse,
<xex>two</xex>-leafed or <xex>two</xex>-leaved, <xex>two</xex>-legged,
<xex>two</xex>-lobed, <xex>two</xex>-masted, <xex>two</xex>-named,
<xex>two</xex>-part, <xex>two</xex>-petaled, <xex>two</xex>-pronged,
<xex>two</xex>-seeded, <xex>two</xex>-sided, <xex>two</xex>-story,
<xex>two</xex>-stringed, <xex>two</xex>-toothed, <xex>two</xex>-valved,
<xex>two</xex>-winged, and the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>One or two</b></col>, <cd>a phrase often used
indefinitely for a small number.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Two</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Two
<hw>Two</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The sum of one
and one; the number next greater than one, and next less than three; two
units or objects.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A symbol representing two units, as 2, II., or
ii.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In two</b></col>, <cd>asunder; into two parts; in halves;
in twain; as, cut <xex>in two</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Two-capsuled</ent>⟦br⟧
